jessicaBlank

By Gary

Pear Note Website

[GD] Let’s talk about you, what do you do?

[J] I am a certified child life specialist, and I work in the inpatient hematology oncology unit here at MOTT. My role is basically to help patients and families cope with being in the hospital, we do that by providing procedure preparation, procedure support, diagnosis education. Different things like that, and we also want to normalize the hospital environment. So a lot of what we do is through play, which I’ve used ZOTT a lot for. 



[GD] Can you describe your work environment? The layout, the structure, the floor. 

[J] The hematology oncology floor is the 7th floor in the hospital. Its a 32 bed unit. The patients each have their own private room. There is a play room in the unit which is where I spend most of my day in and out of. and visiting patients bedside 



[GD] How many patients would you say you are responsible for, or how many do you interact with on a regular basis?



[J] So I would be responsible for all 32 beds. On average I would say i see about 15 patients a day. 



[GD] Are you working with a team of CLS or by yourself ?

[J] I am the only CLS on the 7th floor on my days. I work over the weekend. But during the week there are other people in the unit as well. On mondays I work with a recreational therapist, and then there are other child life specialists, just not ones that I work with directly on the 7th floor.



[GD] Can you describe what a typical day looks like, walk me through when you come in to when you leave? 

[J] Sure, I come in I print a census out with a list of all the patients on the floor, what they’re in for. And they make note after reviewing their chart, patients I need to see, patients with procedures, different things like that. Then I head up to a morning meeting where I touch base with a chidl life specialists on the other units. And then from there its just visting patients. Day to day it kind of changes based on if patients have procedures scheduled or different things like that but the rest of my day is spent touching base with patients, supporting patients as needed. Throughout the day I also do charting work and thats it. 



[GD] Can you describe what your interaction with the patients looks like? 

[J] Yeah. My interaction a lot of the time are either introducing what child life services are to patients and familes, or supporting them during their procedures. For me thats a lot of port access, IV starts , bone marrow biopsies, lumbar punctures, things like that , and then we’ll do procedure preparation for procedures as well. Also as I said before trying to normalize - making sure patients are having experiences that they would be having outside of the hospital. So opportunities to play , socialize with other patients if they want to, coming down to the activity room, doing crafts, playing videogames, those types of things. 



[GD] In the last few weeks can you give me a highlight, for example maybe something you were proud of, disapointed of, suprised with. 

[J] I supported a patient this past week in radiation oncology , it was her simulation, so the visit before she actually starts radiation therapy and they do kind of a practice run - make sure they know how she needs to be positioned during her radiation and she really likes unicorns and brought a book with her and she was able to do the who simulation without any anesthesia with me just reading her the book throughout her simulation so that was awesome. It saved everybody time, money , anesthesia exposure , different things like that. It was really a cool experience . 



[GD] I don’t quite understand what you mean by simulation. 

[J] So in simulation patients come in and they get a CT scan . The image we use for comparison when they do their radiation therapy later on. So we always make sure they are aligned with the image they take during their simulation. So for the patient what that looks like is they have to make a mask or a cradle. Something that helps them stay in that same position through the rest of their radiation treatment, and they have to hold still during the entire time. And then while wearing that mask or being in that cradle they get that CT scan and again they have to hold still through that entire procedure - so sometimes thats difficult for younger kids . And this patient in particular was able to do it with me reading her a book as opposed to being under anesthesia. 



[GD] Could you describe some challenges you’ve faced in the last few weeks?

[J] I am currently transitioning roles, so what comes to mind is I’ve been really busy in preparing for that transition. And moving to a different satellite location thats never had child life before. So doing a lot of work to prepare for that. 



[GD] Is it still in the same hospital?

[J] Its still michigan medicine. Yup just a satellite location. 



[GD] Ok now lets talk about ZOTT. What part do you use? do you use the backned CMS? and the front end? 



[J] Sorry say that again?



[GD] To what extent do you interact with ZOTT?



[J] Right now the way I’ve used it most is we have IPAD that were given to us from you guys on our unit just as like a trial. So theres 9 of them. We have the ZOTT downloaded on all of those ipads. and have been lending them out to patients who would benefit from them. On our floor we get a lot of long term patients. So I would say those have been the patients getting the ipads. And thats how I’ve used the ZOTT app the most. 



[GD] Do you ever interact with the backend part - the CMS - where you can add content, add videos, create events?

[J] I have not, no. 



[GD] Ok have you been trained in it? or have you been shown how it works? 

[J] Yeah I’ve been walked through ZOTT, and we have a digital media manager JJ who you’re familiar with . So he I would say if any of us child life specialists would want to add content we would probably contact him and do it via him. I wouldn’t say we were trained how to add content on our own at this point. 



[GD] I’m kind of curious why people aren’t using backend. Is there just not a need. Or does it not fit into your work style? 

[J] I haven’t ever had anything that I felt needed to be put on there. I think mostly when I’m using it with patients, they are already excited about the things already on there - in terms of the streaming or the games. We did have - I dont know if this went on ZOTT or pre ZOTT but JJ did work with a CLS - actually I think it was pre ZOTT  - they put it on youtube. But a patient worked to make a stop motion video - something with legos. He made a video with legos, you know when you take a bunch of pictures put them together and it looks like they’re moving. I think now that we have ZOTT - had that been something that was made once we were in contact with you guys - that might be something we would consider uploading. I just haven’t had a patient create anything , or created anything myself the need to upload.



[GD] How do you choose that kids or patients you choose to introduce the platform to?

[J] For me what I’ve mostly been using ZOTT for is with those IPADs, typically those are our long term patients. The majority of the time they are bone marrow transplant patients. So they’re here for a minimum of a month. Admitted in the hospital. So that’s who I’ve been using ZOTT with the Most . However I’ve shown the website itself to a lot of lot of patients. I think those that have expressed an interest in playing online games, or in watching streamers or listening to music. If their interests fit with what is on ZOTT, I’ll show them the website. 



[GD] How do kids react to ZOTT? Do they get bored? how long are they using it? 

[J] I don’t know how long they end up using it, when I initially show them. Sometimes there’s some hesitance with the having to create an account, which i know is not really an account - like you are not putting in an email - you’re just picking a nickname and picking a color. Even with that sometimes they don’t even want to go through creating anything, they just want straight access to. it. 



[GD] Is it required to create an account to use it? for the kids? 



[J] From my experience, everytime you open it, it has you pick a user name , your age range, a color, 



[GD] Do you have any reactions from parents? do you introduce ZOTT to them? 

[J] Yes, parents are usually in the room, and I think they are just as excited as the kids to have another resource. And I think they’re extra excited the way Introduce it - is that it is accessible only to hospital patients. So I think that aspect of it makes it really cool. And a lot of times kids have ipads or games they’re constantly playing at home , those are the things they lose interest here at the hospital, so have something that is only accessible here is really cool. And I think theres a lot of value in that. 



[GD] Do have a sense of features in ZOTT are the most popular with kids? 

[J] I think the minecraft is very popular. 



[GD] Has there ever been a time where a patient saw any type of content shouldn’t have been seen , that was inappropaite for the platform? Or do they do a good job of making sure the content is appropriate. 



[J] I haven’t been aware of anything like that. 



[GD] Have you ever set up any in person events or broadcast events?

[J] Correct, I’ve never had to do that. 





[GD] If you have a magic want what would you change about ZOTT?

[J] I remember so one of the perks of ZOTT is that the kids can download the games to their personal devices and keep them. And I remember doing it with a patient one time and it was kind of a nightmare . It just took way to long and you have to use multiple different apps to actually get the download . And I think that it really takes away from it - that its not even really worth the process it takes to get the games. And it would be amazing if that process was simpler. 

[GD] Whats that process like?

[J] Whats that app - I think it was minecraft we were trying to download on a patients computer, and we had to go to a different website. I can’t remember the name of it. And even after that website there was an additional website that we had to do to do the full download. And there was a ZOTT representative with me during this interaction. So I had left the room to see another patient and come back afterwards, and it was still nowhere close to being finished. 



[GD] Do you spend a lot of time troubleshooting problems like that? Or is the platform pretty hands off?

[J] The way I use it - pretty hands off Where I just kind of show it to patients and let them explore as needed and then I’m available if they have questions. 



[Gd] On this IPAD that was provided by ZOTT are there other apps on it? Do kids use it for things that are not ZoTT related?

[J] There are a couple, its pretty limited though. Not very many. 



[GD] For the ZOTT app - do you know if its a dedicated IOS app or is it a website? 

[J] I’m not entirely sure. I think they took the website and made it an app - like bookmarked it. Yeah so it does show up as an app on the ipad but I think its just the bookmarked homepage of ZOTT .



[GD] Is there anything else you want to share with me about how ZOTT is used in your hospital? 

[J] It has benefitted me in some instances one time that I can share, but there was a little girl going down to surgery and it was her first time having surgery. And I was able to give her one of those ipads and go down to surgery with her and the ipads did such an amazing job distracting her and it helped calm her down so much . that was a positive experience that I’ve had. 



[GD] Another question about parents. Has anyone ever expressed interest in being able to control content ? A desire to police the content first? [totally leading question sorry] Or have parents been trusting of whats already on the platform?

[J] Parents have been trusting I think that kind of goes with the technological age - parents are either all or nothing and they either really limit their kids access to technology , or their kids are allowed access then parents are pretty open with it. They are very trusting that we as child life specialists provide.



End and close
